    rectoEn: 'The barrier version of the reverse convertible: what does the client sell instead of the vanilla put?',
    versoEn: 'A DOWN-AND-IN PUT: a put that is only born if the stock has touched a low barrier (say 70) during the product\'s life. Barrier never touched ⇒ capital fully repaid, even if the stock ends at 85; touched ⇒ the vanilla put wakes up. An option that does not always activate is worth less (1.45 versus 5.57 for the vanilla with a 70 barrier) ⇒ smaller premium ⇒ smaller coupon (6.7% versus 10.99%). The barrier is a COMMERCIAL DIAL: no setting gives both the fat coupon and the real protection — only different points on the same frontier.',
