    rectoEn: '"The product is worth 10.50" (Monte Carlo output) — why is the sentence incomplete, and the trap that follows?',
    versoEn: 'The full sentence: "10.50 to within ± 0.09, at 95% confidence" — the mean ± 1.96 standard errors, module 2\'s interval recycled as is. The machine is UNBIASED, it is not PRECISE. The trap: comparing two Monte Carlo prices whose gap is below their standard errors is reading NOISE — the beginner\'s mistake of "seeing" a difference between two runs. And for a desk quoting a 1%-of-notional margin, it dictates the minimum n: the pricing error must be small next to the margin, otherwise the margin itself is noise.',
