    rectoEn: 'The panel: "Why Monte Carlo rather than Black-Scholes?" — the answer that dodges both pitfalls',
    versoEn: 'Reflex: the valuation principle NEVER changes — price = discounted risk-neutral expectation; it is the FORMULA that dies as soon as the payoff depends on the path (minimum, barrier), on several correlated assets (worst-of) or on multiple dates (autocall): the integral loses its closed form, so you estimate it by simulating. The two pitfalls to dodge: believing exotics are priced "differently" (no — same principle), and believing Monte Carlo is more precise (no — 1/√n error: you use it for lack of a formula, never out of greed).',
