    rectoEn: 'The panel: "What are Monte Carlo\'s blind spots?" — both, with the summary sentence',
    versoEn: 'TEMPORAL: between two steps the pricer is blind — a minimum over 12 monthly dates misses intra-month troughs: for a contractually continuous barrier, discrete Monte Carlo structurally UNDERSTATES the price (fixes: more steps, or Broadie-Glasserman-Kou barrier adjustments). DISTRIBUTIONAL: the machine only knows the world it is given — a constant-vol lognormal has no smile, and a low-barrier product lives precisely in the left tail that world sees too thin; a million paths will not change that. The sentence: MONTE CARLO SOLVES THE COMPUTATION PROBLEM, NEVER THE MODEL PROBLEM.',
